 paternalistic relationships between donors and their intended beneficiaries. If philanthropy is to be made compatible with a democratic society of equals, it must be judged not simply on the benefits it brings but on its wider political consequences. Timely and thought-provoking, Private Virtues, Public Vices will challenge readers’ thoughts on what philanthropy is and how it truly affects us.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aCharity organizationxPolitical aspects. 0aDemocracyxSocial aspects. 0aHumanitarianismxPolitical aspects. 0aTesisydisertaciones académicas. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aphilanthropy, democracy, equality, political science, altruism, donations, affect, empathy, paternalism, influence, wealthy, rich, power, control, nonfiction, politics, donors, beneficiaries, humanitarianism, charity, international, foreign aid, giving, ethics, class, sociology, debt, wealth gap, equity, hierarchies, public life.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076650940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226816135423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226816135/original  a978-3-11-076650-9  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles